The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Oct. 8: ONGC has said it would borrow $1 billion to fund its proposed Rs 6,400-crore aromatic petrochemical complex at Mangalore. ONGC Mangalore Petrochemicals has mandated SBI Caps to arrange for the funds for the $1.52-billion plant adjacent to the companys 9.69-million-tonne refinery at the port city, a company official said.                            
	 New Delhi, Oct. 8: Ranbaxy Laboratories said it remained confident that its products were safe and effective as the US Department of Justice withdrew a legal motion against it that charged fraudulent practice. The justice department has been provided with a comprehensive set of audit documents based on instructions by Ranbaxy, a company spokesperson said.                            
	 New Delhi, Oct. 8: The government may allow power generating companies to use surplus coal for a project other than the one for which the block was allotted, as in the the case of Reliance Powers project at Sasan in Madhya Pradesh.                            
	 Mumbai, Oct. 8: The Union Bank of India has introduced a 900-day deposit scheme with a 10.5 per cent interest to depositors. The new to effect from October 6.                             
	 New Delhi, Oct. 8: The finance ministry has sought a fresh clarification from the department of telecom on the proposed segregation of revenues generated from existing 2G and to-be-launched 3G services to work out the annual spectrum usage charges.                             
	 Mumbai, Oct. 8: The Bombay Stock Exchange will start trading on normal timings from October 10. The market will open on at 9.55 am and trading session will end at 3.30 pm.                            
	 New Delhi, Oct. 8: All major markets, including the BSE, the NSE, bullion, metals, steel and foreign exchange, will remain closed tomorrow on account of Dussehra.                                                                                                                          
